Description:¶

In this homework, you will practice (1) going over the full procedure of training a neural network and (2) extending your knowledge on TF2, by implementing a transfer learning task. You will incorporate the existing MobileNets to your own network structure and to classify some new categories of images. Building and fitting the network from scratch is expensive and beyond the scope of this assignment, so you will load the MobileNets model which was pre-trained on the imagenet dataset. The version of MobileNet we're using is V2, which is a family of neural network architectures for efficient on-device image classification and related tasks.

As a general advice, please refer to the official documentations for more info in necessary: Keras, TF Datasets, and TF Hub.

The main difficulty of learninig from this dataset is in the large size of the classes. You may refer to this paper for what other researchers have done with it.

Next, we would like to format all the images for the MobileNet module.


For this module, the size of the input image is fixed to height x width = 224 x 224 pixels. The input images are expected to have 3 RGB color values in the range [0, 1], following the common image input conventions (analogously to TF 1.x).













In [0]:



    


# Initiate the parameters
IMG_SIZE = 224
IMG_SHAPE = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 3)



    













In [0]:



    


# Define a function to format the data 
@tf.function
def format_example(image, label):
    #print("Format example called!")
    # First, convert the data type to tf.float32
    image = tf.dtypes.cast(image, dtype=tf.float32)
    # Second, normalize the image
    image = image / 255.0
    # Third, resize the image 
    image = tf.image.resize(image, (IMG_SIZE,IMG_SIZE))
    return image, label



    













In [0]:



    


# Apply the above function to the previous train_data and test_data,
# to get the formatted training and testing sets, respectively.

train = train_data.map(format_example)
test = test_data.map(format_example)

Reflection Questions:¶
(1) In the data exploration stage, what is the purpose of "assert isinstance(train, tf.data.Dataset)"?















Your Answer: It checks if the class of $\texttt{train}$ and $\texttt{test}$ is $\texttt{tf.data.Dataset}$ in advance to ensure that the following process runs without error. If the class is incorrect it will stop executing following codes.















Part 2: Self-defined CNN¶
In this section, you will define your own CNN to classify the Oxford flowers.


Recall from the tutorial, to build a neural network using tf.keras, there are three steps: defining the model, compiling the model and fitting the model. Each step should be straightforward.


After fitting the model, visualize your model in TensorBoard.


In this stage, we do not ask for a good performance. But please ensure that you obtain a trainable model with no programming bugs.













In [23]:



    


# Step 1: Model definition
# Use a Keras Sequential model for defining your own CNN

# set seed for reproducibility
np.random.seed(0)

model = tf.keras.models.Sequential()
model.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu', input_shape=IMG_SHAPE,
                                 padding='same'))
model.add(tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(2,2))
model.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, (5,5), activation='relu'))
model.add(tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(2,2))
model.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu'))
model.add(tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(2,2))
model.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu'))
model.add(tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(2,2))
model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.25))
model.add(tf.keras.layers.Flatten())
model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'))
model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.25))
model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(102, activation='softmax'))

model.summary()

Reflection Questions:¶
(1) How did you choose your network structure? \
(2) Which optimizer did you use? Why? \















Your Answer:


(1) Since we prefer depth rather than width in a neural network, I choose to introduce 4 convolutional layers and they are connected by averagepooling using a $2\times2$ window. I also adjust the size of filter for each convolutional layer to make the dimension of output even so that there is no issue for averagepooling. Then we flatten the data and densely connect it to a vector of length 256, before we get an output of length 102 using softmax. Dropout technique is used in order to prevent overfitting (although still there turns out to be severe overfitting inspite of using dropout).


(2) I use $\texttt{adam}$ since it is relatively fast computationally and is used by a lot of CNN examples online and course slide.

model_transfer_tuned.compile(optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'sparse_categorical_crossentropy', 
              metrics = ['sparse_categorical_accuracy'])

# model fitting
model_transfer_tuned.fit(train.shuffle(10000).batch(32),
          epochs=5,
          verbose=2,
          callbacks=[tf.keras.callbacks.TensorBoard(log_dir=logs_base_dir, histogram_freq=1)])

# model evaluation
np.random.seed(0)
model_transfer_tuned.evaluate(test.shuffle(10000).batch(32), verbose=2)

Reflection Questions:¶
(1) Briefly explain the network structure of MobileNet and how is it different from other models? \
(2) In your experiment, which parameter(s) is the network most sensitive to? Can you briefly reason why? \
(3) What are some pros and cons of doing transfer learning? \
(4) What is a batch? How does the batch size affect the training process? \
(5) What is an epoch during the training process?















Your Answer:


(1) MobileNet model factorizes a standard convolutional layer into a depthwise convolution and a $1\times1$ convolution called a pointwise convolution. By doing so, training the model will be computationally more effectively with only a slight sacrifice on accuracy.


(2) The number of output units of a convolutional layer and also size of filters. I guess that is because they affect directly the structure of the network.


(3) Pros: we can take advantage of a well-designed network structure that proved to be effective to a problem similar to the unsolved one and apply it to the task at hand, which will save us a lot of time designing the architecture;


Cons: the main architecture is fixed so that we can not do fine-tuning within the pre-trained model accordingly if if does not work as well as we expected.


(4) A batch is a group of data that we feed the network one at a time to train the model. A small batch size would increase the accuracy of training but would be computationally slow, while a large batch size might lose some accuracy, but the training process would be relatively faster.


(5) An epoch is one iteration of the whole training process.
